[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Batch solve time (1000 patients, 50 providers) | 5-15 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Batch solve time (5000 patients, 200 providers) | 30-90 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Real-time single-patient scoring | < 200ms |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Optimality gap (60s time limit) | 0-2% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Override rate (well-tuned weights) | 5-15% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Panel balance improvement vs. manual | 30-50% reduction in variance |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** When constraints are too tight (every provider is at capacity, limited network overlap), the solver returns infeasible. When weights don't reflect actual clinical priorities, assignments look "optimal" but feel wrong to clinicians, leading to high override rates. When source data is stale (provider left last week but directory not updated), assignments point to providers who can't accept patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The math is the easy part. Seriously. Formulating and solving the optimization model is a solved problem. A competent engineer can have a working solver in a week.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The hard part is getting agreement on the weights. "How much is language concordance worth relative to geographic proximity?" is not a technical question. It's a clinical and operational question with political dimensions. Different stakeholders have different answers. The medical director cares about continuity. The CFO cares about panel balance (empty panels mean lost revenue). The patient experience team cares about language and proximity. You will spend more time in meetings about weights than you will writing code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m My advice: start with equal weights, run the solver, show the results to stakeholders, and iterate. Let the override patterns tell you where the weights are wrong. If panel managers consistently override language-discordant assignments, your language weight is too low. Build a feedback loop, not a committee.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The other surprise: data quality is the binding constraint, not solver performance. Provider directories are notoriously inaccurate. A provider marked as "accepting new patients" who actually closed their panel two weeks ago. A specialty listed as "internal medicine" when the provider actually focuses on geriatrics. Insurance network participation that changed last quarter but hasn't been updated. Garbage in, garbage out applies with particular force to optimization. The solver will confidently produce the optimal assignment given the data you feed it, even if that data is wrong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One more thing: the "simple" classification in the planning doc is accurate for the optimization itself, but the organizational change management is anything but simple. Providers are accustomed to controlling their own panels. Telling them "the algorithm assigned you 47 new patients this month" requires trust, transparency, and the ability to override. Build the override mechanism first, not last.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Provider departure redistribution.** When a provider leaves, their entire panel needs reassignment. Same solver, different trigger: instead of unassigned patients, the input is the departing provider's full panel. Add a continuity bonus for the provider who most recently covered for the departing one. This is the highest-stakes use of the system because patients are losing an existing relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity-weighted panel balancing.** Raw patient counts don't capture workload. A panel of 1,500 patients with multiple chronic conditions is harder than 2,000 healthy patients. Weight each patient by a complexity score (HCC risk score, number of active conditions, visit frequency) and balance on weighted panel load rather than headcount. This requires the risk scoring infrastructure from Chapter 7.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-site optimization.** For health systems with multiple clinic locations, add a site-assignment layer. Patients are assigned to a provider-site pair, and the solver balances across sites as well as providers. This adds geographic access constraints and site-level capacity limits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.1 (Appointment Slot Optimization):** Optimizes the time slots that providers offer; complementary to panel assignment which determines which patients fill those slots
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.4 (Nurse Staffing Optimization):** Uses similar MIP formulation for staff-to-shift assignment with more complex labor constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.6 (Rising Risk Identification):** Produces the risk scores that can weight panel complexity in the extended version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.1 (Internal Duplicate Patient Detection):** Clean patient records are a prerequisite; duplicate patients create phantom panel inflation
